                <note rend="inline" type="source">721.2315/79: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McMillin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-25T12:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 25, 1919, noon.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 10.58 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Confidential. Department’s June 18th, 5 p.m. Yesterday, orally, informally, I
                    intimated to the Minister for Foreign Affairs the course I thought best for Peru
                    in Colombian frontier dispute. The Minister for Foreign Affairs seemed entirely
                    reasonable saying that Peru and Colombia are in substantial accord on
                    arbitration and tribunal, differing as to the extent of territory submitted. He
                    said that Peru is ready to submit all their controversies to the League of
                    Nations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McMillin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
